            <td>~$560B</td>
            <td>~$75B</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Focus</td>
            <td class="highlight">Top 100 Nasdaq (ex-financials)</td>
            <td>Broad US large-cap</td>
            <td>US info technology sector</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Dividend Yield</td>
            <td class="highlight">~0.55%</td>
            <td>~1.3%</td>
            <td>~0.6%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>5-Year Return</td>
            <td class="highlight">~140%</td>
            <td>~85%</td>
            <td>~155%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>10-Year Return</td>
            <td class="highlight">~430%</td>
            <td>~220%</td>
            <td>~500%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Number of Holdings</td>
            <td class="highlight">101</td>
            <td>503</td>
            <td>316</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Key takeaway:</strong> QQQ sits between SPY and VGT in terms of tech concentration. SPY offers broad diversification, VGT is a pure tech play, and QQQ blends heavy tech exposure with consumer discretionary and communication services stocks.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Annual Returns Bar Chart -->
  <div class="qqq-section">
    <h2>QQQ Annual Returns (2015–2025)</h2>
    <p>QQQ's year-by-year performance shows the potential for outsized gains — and painful drawdowns. The fund posted nearly 55% in 2023 during the AI-driven rally, but lost over 32% in 2022 during the rate-hiking cycle.</p>
